For Dionysius took the word ‘pitiable’ in the sense of ‘patlietic‚ full of pathos,' and knowing that pathos was one of the points of a good poet, understood the criticism as praise, while the company, accepting the real sense ‘utterly pitiable,’ realised that the prince was guilty of a genuine lapse.1
